    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-30T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-30T15:00:00-05:00" n="119"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d119">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">810.20 Defense/181<hi rend="superscript"
                    >1/10</hi>: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hinkle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ciudad Trujillo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-30T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >May 30, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 6:02 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>83. Department’s telegram No. 61, May 29, noon [<hi rend="italic">3
                        p.m.</hi>]<note n="42" xml:id="d119fn1">See footnote 29, <ref
                            target="#pg_16">p. 16</ref>.</note> The President<note n="43"
                        xml:id="d119fn2">Manuel de Jesus Troncoso de la Concha.</note> said that his
                    Government was entirely in accord with the Department’s suggestion and that it
                    would be ready to put into operation at any time. The President added that
                    General Trujillo authorized him to offer any type of cooperation whatsoever.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hinkle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
